<TEXT>
a decision last year by saudi arabia to reduce 
import subsidies has made a big impact on world barley trade 
including us shipments says the agriculture department 
barley is not a huge crop nationally but it is important to 
many farmers and is an essential part of the us food machine 
last year by comparison barley output was 527 million bushels 
and corn 706 billion bushels 
world barley trade grew explosively over the last two decades 
and has shown signs of leveling off only in the last year says 
pete riley of the departments economic research service 
barley trade accelerated during the 1980s when world traffic in 
other grains experienced severe contractions riley said the gains 
were supported by increases in exportable barley supplies and by 
export subsidies notably by the european economic community the 
largest exporter 
one of the key factors in demand has been the dramatic rise in 
imports by saudi arabia now the worlds largest barley importer 
sparked by import subsidies he said 
besides the eec the main barley exporters are canada the 
united states and australia others which are comparatively small 
include austria finland new zealand and sweden and finland and 
sweden are expected to become net importers riley said 
the most remarkable barley development has been the increase in 
saudi arabias imports from less than 100000 metric tons in the 
mid1970s to 85 million tons in 198687 import subsidies 
equivalent to 81 per ton 176 per bushel were the key factor 
a metric ton is about 2205 pounds and is equal to 459 bushels 
of barley 
riley said the saudi import subsidies sometimes exceeded the 
price of the grain itself 
the reason for such large subsidies was saudi arabias 
commitment to improve consumer diets and to support a large number 
of sheep imported live every year for moslem pilgrims he said as 
imports increased so did saudi reserve stockpiles of barley 
but the import subsidies were reduced 67 percent last september 
and saudi imports are expected to decline in 198788 to 55 million 
tons even so saudi arabia will still be the leading barley 
importer well above the next largest the soviet union which is 
expected to import 3 million tons 
in addition to budget considerations one motivation for the 
saudi cut in subsidies was an attempt to increase domestic 
production riley said in the april issue of agricultural outlook 
magazine recent increases in the producer price have failed to 
bring a big response and 198788 output is forecast at less than 
150000 tons 
meanwhile us barley production could decline this year from 
the 1987 harvest of 527 million bushels which was down from the 
record of 6105 million bushels in 1986 north dakota is the 
leading barley producer with 1392 million bushels last year 
according to a recent usda report farmers may plant 103 
million acres for harvest in 1988 down 7 percent from last year 
barley exports in the 198788 marketing year which runs through 
may 31 are forecast at 115 million bushels down from 137 million 
last season in 198586 us barley exports were reported at 22 
million bushels 
