<TEXT>
twentythree cars of a 135car freight train 
derailed along the columbia river and two of the cars leaked 
hazardous chemicals authorities said 
no one was hurt in fridays derailment but the singletrack 
line was blocked and was not expected to be reopened until sunday 
the burlington northern train was carrying primarily lumber and 
other forest products along with some chemicals ore pumice 
aluminum bars and other industrial goods 
one tank car landed on its side on the river bank and leaked 
sodium borohydride a chemical used in bleaching wood pulp and 
manufacturing plastic foam the other leaking car tumbled partly 
into the river spilling sodium borohydroxide a closely related 
chemical used in chemical manufacturing petroleum products and 
papermaking said howard kallio a spokesman for burlington 
northern 
both chemicals produce heat as they dissolve in water but are 
not explosive kallio said they can be harmful if people breathe 
the vapor or dust or come in contact with the substances he added 
dave hare chief of the benton county hazardous materials team 
said more than half the sodium borohydroxide in the partially 
submerged tanker spilled into the river before the leak was stopped 
mcnary dam about 23 miles downstream was closed for nearly 2 
hours to increase the dilution of the chemical before it passed 
farther west eliminating any possibility of danger from the spill 
he said 
the leaking car on the riverbank also contained sodium chloride 
hare said hazardous materials team members tightened bolts on the 
dome of that car to stop the leak 
cleanup of the derailed cars will take three or four days 
kallio said 
the cause of the accident which took place about eight miles 
east of plymouth was undetermined the allowable track speed was 
60 mph but kallio said he did not know the actual speed of the 
train 
amtrak passenger trains were being rerouted to union pacific 
tracks on the oregon side of the river he said 
