<TEXT>
news leaks protests and philippine 
press commentaries have clouded the atmosphere in talks between 
american and filipino officials on the status of us military 
bases here 
last tuesday the two sides began a threemonth review of the 
1947 military bases agreement which allows the united states to 
use six military installations in the philippines 
us and filipino officials say the outcome is expected to 
influence manilas decision on whether to allow the bases to remain 
after the agreement expires in 1991 
both sides have called for a cordial review but there are 
increasing calls in the philippines for closing the bases and for 
asserting nationalism in dealings with the former colonial power 
on saturday foreign secretary raul manglapus chief philippine 
negotiator reiterated his claim that the bases serve us and not 
filipino interests 
he also challenged claims by ambassador nicholas platt chairman 
of the us panel that the installations are vital to counteract 
soviet expansionism 
we are under attack from within not from without manglapus 
said referring to communist rebels and rightwing extremists 
missiles aimed at some external target do not help us in this 
internal struggle we recognize no enemies but those within our 
borders 
the atmosphere between the two panels soured early when filipino 
officials leaked details of a dispute over manilas demand that the 
americans obtain prior consent before launching combat operations 
from the bases 
the us panel boycotted a scheduled session thursday morning 
and american sources said platt was furious over the leak 
but predictably most manila newspapers viewed american anger as 
an example of washington pressuring the filipino panel in the 
talks commentators urged the philippine government to stand its 
ground 
our panel should send back a clear message of standing pat on 
its commitment to making a more equitable arrangement through 
primarily gaining a bigger compensation package for the bases stay 
in the philippines for the duration of the agreement wrote the 
manila journal 
prominent columnist art borjal wrote in the philippine daily 
star that the filipino panel has an obligation to bargain for more 
philippine control of the bases the installations are nominally 
under philippine command although effectively under us control 
just about everybody is supporting the view that the 
philippines should protect its sovereignty stand its ground and 
bargain with the americans as a coequal nation borjal wrote 
groups opposed to the us bases are planning to take advantage 
of the antiamerican sentiment to stage more protests 
on friday riot police used clubs and jets of water to stop a 
protest outside the us embassy by about 3000 people demanding an 
end to the american bases 
officers attacked when some demonstrators broke away from the 
main group and dashed for the embassy some people in the crowd 
threw stones at police 
nationalist sentiment is expected to sharpen when the two panels 
take up the sensitive issues of compensation and nuclear weapons 
the filipinos are expected to demand substantial increases in the 
180 million they receive annually from washington for use of the 
bases 
a clause in the new filipino constitution also states the 
philippines opposes nuclear weapons consistent with the national 
interest 
legislation has been filed in the senate to ban nuclear weapons 
from the philippines and bar nuclearpowered ships from ports 
because of nationalistic fervor drummed up by the bases talks 
an accidental overflight of the presidential palace by a us navy 
helicopter emerged as a major topic in the local press 
a spokesman for the us navy at subic bay said the helicopter 
inadvertently flew over the prohibited air space last tuesday 
during a delivery flight to the us embassy the aircraft flew 
across the restricted area a mile north of the palace 
the manila bulletin wrote the unlawful buzzing by a us navy 
helicopter made us think of the human cost exacted even in 
peacetime by the warmaking machine at clark and subic the 
principle involved being that a war machine claims human lives even 
when it is idle 
on saturday kenneth quinn deputy chief of mission at the us 
embassy apologized for the incident and promised it would not 
happen again 
