here is a transcript of the response saturday 
by sen lloyd bentsen dtexas to president reagans weekly radio 
address 
on behalf of hundreds of democrats and republicans in congress 
i want to invite president reagan to stop brandishing his veto pen 
and accept the hand of friendship and work with us to fashion 
fair effective trade policies that will help america prosper in 
the 21st century 
late last week house and senate negotiators agreed on the 
outlines of comprehensive legislation that would finally establish 
trade policy as an urgent national priority it would put the world 
and our own government on notice that trade will no longer be 
the neglected stepchild of american policy 
its objective would be that countries which have full access to 
our market should grant us full access to their markets this 
legislation enjoys broad bipartisan support 
there are those who believe this bill doesnt do enough and 
there are those who prefer that we do nothing who like to conjure 
up images of the discredited smoothawley tariff thats unfair 
its like saying that anyone who supports a strong national defense 
is a warmonger 
and in this instance its especially unfair because the 
compromise trade bill is designed to resist protectionism by 
opening world markets and enforcing trade laws 
later this month well tie up the loose ends of the 
legislation bring it to a vote in congress and send it to the 
white house 
i would hope the president will sign it in the same spirit of 
bipartisanship which prevailed after the october 19 stock market 
crash six months ago at that time we all sat down together 
republicans and democrats white house and congress we set aside 
narrow partisan political differences and we hammered out some 
honest answers to the difficult problem of deficit reduction 
today we have an opportunity to take the same approach to the 
equally important problem of the trade deficit we just cant 
afford to be lulled into a false sense of security by the recent 
welcome surge in american exports monthly or quarterly economic 
snapshots dont accurately describe how trade has been a tragedy 
for the american worker during this decade 
let me give you an example of what i mean since 1981 our 
exports have stagnated while our imports have increased by 60 
percent thats why we had a 171 billion trade deficit last year 
this failure of exports to keep pace with imports has cost 
american dearly if exports had grown only onethird as rapidly as 
imports we would have created a million and a half jobs for 
american workers 
but jobs are only part of the story our soaring trade deficits 
have been matched by soaring international debt four years ago 
america was the worlds largest creditor nation today we are the 
largest debtor nation with international obligations of over 400 
billion we owe more money than mexico brazil argentina and 
venezuala combined 
for many years trade has sat below the salt when it comes to 
american policy and during the past seven years of growing trade 
deficits it hs remained there foreign policy monetary policy 
strategic policy have all taken precedence over trade random 
ineffective protectionist actions have served as a surrogate for 
trade policy 
no one suggests that the bipartisan trade bill congress will 
soon send to the president will solve all of americas problems 
with trade and restore our competitiveness 
but we cant do the job without a consistent trade policy to 
point us in the right direction to shield us from protectionist 
pressures by opening world markets to american manufactured and 
agricultural products to create new opportunities for our service 
industries to accord trade policy the importance it so clearly 
deserves and to demonstrate that america is serious about insisting 
on equal access to world markets 
the trade bill well send to the president gives america the 
tools we need to do a very difficult important job it is the 
bipartisan product of consultation and compromise it will help 
produce a stronger more competitive american presence in the world 
markets 
so with colleagues on both sides of the aisle i urge the 
president to sign the trade bill and join congress in creating an 
effective bipartisan american response to the challenge of trade 
</TEXT>
