private pleas from arabs and israelis and his 
own instincts keep secretary of state george p shultz engaged in a 
middle east peace effort that has produced little progress so far 
shultz left the troubled region friday vowing to return 
convinced that all the key parties israel jordan and palestinian 
arabs want to work out a settlement 
he refused to be sidetracked by israeli prime minister yitzhak 
shamirs resistance to a symbolic peace conference that would 
launch the negotiations nor was he unnerved by a government 
statement in amman only hours after he left that jordan would not 
stand in for the palestinians 
shultz said israelis are as interested in peace and stability 
as jordan and the palestinians perhaps even more so he 
suggested the jordanian statement was designed for public 
consumption and did not reflect a more amenable stand taken 
privately by king hussein 
two of the basic elements in shultzs plan are a peace 
conference and exclusion of the palestine liberation organization 
he said in an interview in amman that the plo sought to exterminate 
israel officials kept it off the air 
shultz would have palestinians at the table but as part of a 
delegation with jordan he publicly opposed establishment of a 
palestinian state in the blackedout interview 
in jerusalem shultz tried to convince shamir that the peace 
conference he opposed was not the one shultz had in mind the 
