<TEXT>
after a week of waiting the united states on 
saturday received a written soviet response to a reagan 
administration proposal for continued superpower military support 
for the factions in afghanistan us officials said 
and secretary of state george p shultz as he studied the 
response considered a trip to geneva this week to attend the 
signing of a longawaited accord ending soviet troop presence in 
afghanistan 
the united states had called on moscow to confirm in writing 
that it accepted the us compromise on the issue of military 
assistance to afghan elements after the soviets carry out a plan to 
remove their estimated 115000 troops from afghanistan 
no details of the soviet response were revealed however the 
soviets earlier this week were reported to have informally 
accepted the us proposal 
sondra mccarty a state department spokeswoman said shultz had 
received a response from soviet foreign minister eduard a 
shevardnadze and its being studied 
the reply was turned over to the us embassy in moscow and 
cabled to washington said another us official speaking on 
condition of anonymity he said shultz may go to geneva to join 
shevardnadze at the signing ceremony of a comprehensive 
unsponsored afghan settlement 
shultz returned friday night from a grueling fivecountry 
sixday trip to the middle east and has already scheduled an april 
1926 trip that will take him to moscow to prepare for president 
reagans may 29june 2 summit with soviet leader mikhail gorbachev 
un mediator diego cordovez announced on friday after six years 
of negotiations that an accord was ready for signature by 
representatives of pakistan and the warring afghan government and 
resistance forces 
under the accord the soviets would start pulling their troops 
out of afghanistan on may 15 and complete the withdrawal in nine 
months with half the soviet soldiers leaving in the first three 
months 
afghan refugees mostly in pakistan would be allowed to return 
home and afghanistan would become a neutral and nonaligned nation 
under us and soviet guarantees 
the us proposal permits the superpowers to continue military 
support for their clients in afghanistan the moscowbacked 
government in kabul and the mujahedeen rebels who have been 
receiving us weapons 
shultz had hoped the soviets would agree to a mutual cutoff of 
aid to the factions in afghanistan but the soviets asserted their 
right to keep supplying the kabul government so the united states 
suggested an agreement on mutual continuation of aid 
officials in washington said the deal could eventually lead to a 
cessation of aid if the soviets decide to stop assisting the 
afghan government the united states might be prepared to follow 
suit with a symmetrical cessation of its aid to the resistance 
us aid including portable stinger antiaircraft missiles said 
to have downed hundreds of soviet helicopters and planes has been 
credited by resistance leaders and us officials as the key 
assistance element that permitted afghan guerrillas to wage 
effective campaigns against the soviet troops 
moscow sent its army into afghanistan in december 1979 to take 
control of antiguerrilla operations the prosoviet afghan army had 
been waging ineffectively and to oust a kabul government whose 
support for soviet policies was wavering 
</TEXT>
