jurors also heard mrs cipollones own words in a deposition made 
before her death at age 58 in 1984 
on wednesday cipollone testified 
he is seeking damages from the defendants lorillard inc 
philip morris co and liggett group inc charging that they 
failed to do enough research on cigarettes and health to tell the 
public what they did know and to put a safer product on the market 
the industry which has never lost such a case is focusing on 
the individual as the key to its defense which began thursday 
the companies argue that it was mrs cipollones choice to smoke 
as an intelligent independent and strongwilled woman who knew the 
risks of smoking at least as articulated by critics the industry 
does not acknowledge that cigarettes are a proven cause of cancer 
the companies began presenting their case with an economic 
historian who testified about the information mrs cipollone would 
have had available to her namely hundreds of articles on the 
risks of smoking that appeared in newspapers she read 
