almost immediately and walked through police lines to be greeted by 
hugs from friends and cheers from supporters 
carol herrmann executive assistant to the president said the 
administration had no choice but to arrest the students when hours 
of negotiations failed to get them to leave the building 
i hope it wont alienate the black community i think that the 
administration is ready always to address concerns of campus 
environment she said 
i think it went very smoothly stormer said there was no 
resistance in the form of being combative they merely resisted in 
the form of holding onto each other 
about 130 protesters were in the building when police started 
making arrests but many chose to leave rather than face 
prosecution stormer said 
craig millar assistant vice president for student services 
told the students who were arrested they also face charges under 
the universitys code of conduct and could be expelled 
operations at the telecommunications building which houses the 
universitys central switchboard were not interrupted by the 
student protest university spokesman roger williams said 
