official questioned how the fine was calculated investigators were 
told friday 
the official federal aviation administration regional counsel 
donald boberick testified during a national transportation safety 
board hearing probing the nov 23 crash of ryan air flight 103 
the crash was the 10th ryan air accident in eight years four 
involved fatalities the november crash was the nations worst 
commuter airline crash in 19 years only three of the 21 people 
aboard the twinengine commuter plane survived 
during the 2day hearing the fourmember ntsb panel has 
pointed out previous ryan air violations and wanted to know why the 
proposed 250000 fine for scores of record and flight violations 
was slashed to 16500 
ryan air has sought protection from creditors under chapter 11 
of federal bankruptcy laws its planes were grounded in january as 
part of a consent agreement with the faa ryan air had been 
alaskas largest commuter airline serving more than 80 cities and 
communities 
the 250000 fine was recommended by faa operations inspector 
lou gossen after he inspected ryan air 10 months before the crash 
boberick said gossen had calculated that ryan air should have a 
penalty equivalent to the loss of profit for 15 days but that he 
rejected the proposal because it was not a recognized method of 
calculating sanctions 
fines can range from 100 to 1000 for each violation boberick 
said a revised proposal following that guideline was then submitted 
to his office with the fine reduced to 25000 the lawyer said 
further review by his office lowered the fine to 16500 because 
some violations had been counted more than once and some were 
given the maximum fine when they should not have been 
gossen had considered prior infractions in figuring the 250000 
proposed fine but boberick said he had not been aware of earlier 
violations 
a final ntsb report on the november crash is expected later this 
year 
